1ï¸âƒ£ What is Event Handling?

Event Handling is the mechanism that allows a program to respond to user actions such as:

Button click

Mouse movement

Keyboard input

In Java Swing, event handling follows the Eventâ€“Listener Model.

2ï¸âƒ£ Eventâ€“Listener Model

Java uses the Delegation Event Model which has three main parts:

Event Source
â†’ Component that generates the event
Example: JButton

Event Object
â†’ Contains information about the event
Example: ActionEvent

Event Listener
â†’ Object that receives and handles the event
Example: ActionListener

3ï¸âƒ£ Event Handling in Online Banking System
ğŸ”¸ Event Source
JButton create = new JButton("Create");
JButton login = new JButton("Login");
JButton deposit = new JButton("Deposit");
JButton withdraw = new JButton("Withdraw");

ğŸ”¸ Event Listener Registration
create.addActionListener(e -> createAccount());
login.addActionListener(e -> login());
deposit.addActionListener(e -> doTransaction(true));
withdraw.addActionListener(e -> doTransaction(false));


Here:

addActionListener() registers the listener

Lambda expression acts as the listener

ğŸ”¸ Event Object

When a button is clicked, an ActionEvent object is automatically created by Swing.

ActionEvent e

4ï¸âƒ£ Event Processing (Step-by-Step Flow)
âœ… Example: CREATE Button

Step 1: User clicks Create
Step 2: ActionEvent is generated
Step 3: Listener captures the event
Step 4: createAccount() method executes
Step 5: Account object is created
Step 6: Data is saved to database
Step 7: Output displayed in text area

5ï¸âƒ£ Code for Event Processing
Create Account Event
create.addActionListener(e -> createAccount());

void createAccount() {
    // Validation
    // Object creation
    // Database save
    // Output display
}

Login Event
login.addActionListener(e -> login());

void login() {
    // Fetch account
    // Password verification
    // Display balance
}

Deposit / Withdraw Event
deposit.addActionListener(e -> doTransaction(true));
withdraw.addActionListener(e -> doTransaction(false));

void doTransaction(boolean dep) {
    // Thread creation
    // Deposit or withdraw
    // Update database
}

6ï¸âƒ£ Multithreading in Event Processing

To prevent UI freezing:

Thread t = new TransactionThread(current, amt, dep);
t.start();
t.join();


âœ” Ensures:

Safe transaction

No race condition

UI responsiveness

7ï¸âƒ£ Advantages of Event Handling

âœ” User-friendly interaction
âœ” Separation of UI and logic
âœ” Dynamic response to user actions
âœ” Scalable design

8ï¸âƒ£ Event Handling in Servlets (Short Note)

In Servlets, events are HTTP Requests.

protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest req,
                      HttpServletResponse res)


âœ” Request acts as event
âœ” Servlet processes event
âœ” Response sent back to client
